The Role of Tif1 in Primitive and Definitive Erythropoiesis .
Taken together , our data suggest that tif1 is required as a permissive cofactor for the erythroid lineage-specific control of hematopoietic <termsem="SO:0000704"> gene </term> expression .
We reasonably predict that Tif1 protein functions as a transcriptional intermediary factor in hematopoietic progenitor cells given that both TIF1 ( Zhong et al. 1999 ) and TIF1 ( Friedman et al. 1996 ; Abrink et al. 2001 ) have been shown to act as intermediary factors that positively or negatively regulate <termsem="SO:0000704"> gene </term> transcription .
These studies indicate that TIF1 and TIF1 act as scaffolds that link different classes of <termsem="SO:0000352"> DNA </term> - binding proteins and chromatin-associated proteins into larger regulatory complexes .
Tif1 is detected within nuclear foci ( see Figure 6 ) , which , based on our analysis , do not appear to correspond to several types of previously described nuclear bodies , including PML bodies .
Localization of Tif1 to these nuclear bodies may be regulated by posttranslational modification such as SUMO modification that is required for PML to form PML nuclear domains ( Zhong et al. 2000a , 2000b ; Best et al. 2002 ) .
These foci may serve as assembly points where Tif1 forms multisubunit complexes with <termsem="SO:0000352"> DNA </term> - binding transcription factors and their other essential coactivators or corepressors , during the early stages of erythroid differentiation .
It will be important to determine the identity of Tif1-interacting proteins in nuclear foci and establish how they function with Tif1 to regulate blood cell development .
